<br>
Good.  So, can I also assume that if they do have a full understanding of the situation at hand, you would fully support their actions (or at least allow for it)?<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Seriously think about that comment for awhile and you will know that it is wrong on so many levels it is ludicrous.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dictionary.com/search?q=communism">Communism</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dictionary.com/search?q=Democracy">Democracy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The opposite of Communism is Laissez-Faire (free market/Capitalism) system.<br>
<br>
The opposite of Democracy is a Dictatorship.<br>
<br>
All practical examples of Communist states have been under a Dictatorship.  However, many so-called free market countries, such as the US, have very socialist programs set up.  Health care and welfare are the most clear examples.  But things like minimum wage, and government union support are also examples.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Wasn’t it the US who declared pre-emptive strikes a valid defence policy?&quot;<br>
<br>
Pre-emptive strikes against a known enemy in the time of war is one thing.  Another thing entirely is going into a building or home of someone that you have absolutely no solid, valid knowledge of without a search warrent.  That's why they have search warrents in the first place.<br>
<br>
Something that I am finding hard to take in here is that so many people think that because this is a different type of threat, we somehow need to change the rules for this situation.  That's not how it works.  When it does work that way we call it Martial Law.  Believe it or not, that is how so many Democracies have turned into Dictatorships.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The Zero Samurai--I agree with a lot you've said, but my biggest problem is that almost everything you've said was purely idealogical. You need to put a lot of your claims into a contemporary context--that is to say the threat of terrorism will sooner or later have to suppress some one's say in things.&quot;<br>
<br>
You're right.  I am not using a context using current events.  I am not doing so for a specific reason though.  I think that what I am saying can be applied to more than just the current situation.  As for saying that terrorism is going to suppress views, well maybe.  But if it gets to the point where my basic constitutional rights are being banned because of it, I myself will be out into the street with a picket sign and burning any flag that I see necessary to set things straight. <p><br>
