<br>
You say that pre-emptive strikes are relevant in times of war. Well it was the United States government as well as their allies (one of which is Australia) who declared the “War on Terror.” And while it is just a title for the situation and not an actual declaration of war, due to such a war being technically impossible, they have recognized that the gravity of the situation has deemed it necessary to be titled as such. And also, why would intelligence agencies declare to the world their evidence? You seem to think that because they do not officially broadcast it, evidence doesn’t exist. They would not act unless they perceived a very real threat on the people they are sworn to protect. <br>
<br>
These agencies are also granted the mandate to act in the best interest of the nation without deference to the nation. Here lies the recognition that often democracy is too slow in terms of implementation.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, you talk of the situation as if it would deteriorate into “Martial Law.” Well, intelligence agencies are not to martial organizations, so that would not, and could not, be the eventuality.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Something that I am finding hard to take in here is that so many people think that because this is a different type of threat, we somehow need to change the rules for this situation. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Every situation demands accommodation. A great example of this is justified force. If someone threatens you with a spoon, you retaliate with equal force. If someone threatens the lives of hundreds with a bomb strapped to his chest, you have every endorsement of the law to kill him. It is the same with potential threats. If these people who are being arrested were suspected car jackers then I would see no reason for forced entry. But that is not the case. They are potential criminals of great magnitude.  <br>
