<br>
First off, you seemed to have switched your stance just subtly enough to coincide with the terms that I put to the situation.  I already said that if these people are known enemies of the state, then fine, let the enforcement agencies do their jobs.  I never said you had to go and divulge all information to the public.  That is a matter of national security.<br>
<br>
What I am saying, and this is what you were talking about, is illegal search and seizure.  If there is proper evidence, then fine.  Keep it secret all you want.  The only people that need to know are the agencies and the judge that apporved the warrant.  How do you decide what is proper evidence (or cause)?  Simple, the judge does that.  That is why they are there.  If a judge decides that because the case is different, due to some threat of terrorism, then let him make that decision.  When you get rid of the process you remove the ability to let you government run as an autonomous unit.<br>
<br>
The main problem with your new view of the situation is that you assume that &quot;they would not act unless they perceived a very real threat on the people they are sworn to protect.&quot;  Now who's being impractical?  I mean c'mon, you can't really believe that.  If I were the head of an enforcement agency, I might be more than just a little tempted to use the current situation, one where I don't need to explain my actions to the public, to my advantage.  Why not take out a couple of tough to get criminals in the interim?<br>
<br>
You are right, however, that every situation demands some sort of accommodation.  The difference between you and I, is that there are just some accommodations I am unwilling to make.  Some things are just too far.  No matter how great the benifit.  The entire point of terrorism is to bring a nation to the point you are saying we should go.  If a country does not stand steadfast in at least its core virtues then it loses agains terrorism, no matter how many terrorists are killed.<br>
<br>
<br>
As for your complete and utter disbelief that you don't actually know the definitions of Communism and Democracy, and their relation to one another, I just don't know.  I think I am going to give this one last shot and then declair it a lost cause here.<br>
<br>
Scenario A) Mr. Dictator takes over Littlecountryland.  Mr. Dictator now decides that he wants everyone to get an exact equal share of everything.  Mr. Dictator sets up a financial system (Communism) where all jobs pay the same and all products are standardized.<br>
<br>
Scenario B) Mr. Dictator decides that Communism sucks and he doesn't have the means to drive his country to succeed because all products are standard and yet the general quality has gone severily down.  Now he wants businesses to compete so that the best one will sell more.  Also, he allows the economy to decide what people's wage will be based on how much the market decides their function is worth.  Now Mr. Dictator has implemented a Free Market system.  Now all Mr. Dictator has to worry about is public safty and foreign affairs.  Yea!<br>
<br>
Scenario C) The people of Littlecountryland are sick and tire of being told what to do.  They get a group together, overthrow Mr. Dictator and bring in Mr. Democracy.  Mr Democracy is only in term for a set amount of years though.  That way the people have an option to vote him to stay or boot his sorry @ss out on the Littlecountryland street.  In the midst of all their new found voting rights, the people decide they liked things in a Free Market and want to keep that system.  They hold a big ol' vote and now, they are a Democracy with Capitalism.<br>
<br>
Scenario D) Littlecountryland has been struck with hard times and they decide they need to have social saftey nets.  Littlecountryland sets up a social security system, increased welfare, and even raises minimum wages to match most professional jobs.  Now the professionals think to themselfs heck, I should just take one of those jobs.  The market becomes flooded with unskilled labor because everyone is in the wrong field.  This sucks, good thing they can vote themselves back out of this Communist state.  Unfortunately it will take decades of foreign relief to put things back to their former glory.<br>
<br>
We could go on like this all day, or at least I could.  I'm in my fourth year as an economics major.  You need to understand that just because the foot and the hand are two parts of the same machine, that does not make them the same thing.  That principal applies to economic and political systems.  Hell, if we let the economic system govern us, we would be so much better off.  Unfortunately, we let officials get in the way and muck it all up. <p><br>
