<br>
Ok, I take it back - Britain does have a constitution of sorts...<br>
<br>
...but it's not a very good one. Have you ever read the Magna Carta?<br>
<br>
The first point is an attempt by the church to maintain control of their considerable holdings. It can be read to mean that the church is only answerable to god, not even the state.<br>
<br>
A large proportion deals directly with the upper classes maintaining control. Inheritence and protection of status are the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th and 8th points raised.<br>
<br>
...so there's 8 points and we're not even onto free-speech yet...<br>
<br>
No, wait, I don't think that's in there...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If one who has borrowed from the Jews any sum, great or small, die before that loan be repaid, the debt shall not bear interest while the heir is under age<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Er...right...This is point 10 of around 60. This seem relevent to anyone? No, thought not. You can't legally transfer debt to an heir in Britain - so don't tell me the Magna Carta is a constitution!<br>
<br>
There's also an interesting point about Earls and Barons only being prosecuted by their peers...right, and that's a good model for a fair legal system is it?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No one shall be arrested or imprisoned upon the appeal of a woman, for the death of any other than her husband<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Oh, I like that one. Pre womens-rights obviously! That's point 54 I think...<br>
<br>
<br>
I can't read anymore. It's laughable. Just accept that the majority of the rest deals with Knights!<br>
<br>
One more important point - the Magna Carta has no legal standing today, and is only of interest to historians.<br>
